 | accessdate = 2009-01-08
 }}</ref>

== Shooting ==
On the day of the shooting, the start of school had been delayed by snow and not all students had arrived when the shooting began.<ref name="KOLOTV" /> Just before 9:00 a.m. ([[UTC-8]]), fourteen-year-old student James Scott Newman brought his mother's [[.38 caliber]] [[revolver]] to school in his backpack.<ref name="NewsReview" /><ref name="LasVegasReview">{{cite news
 | first = Sandra
 | last = Chereb
 | coauthors = Kara Tsuboi, Ed Pearce
 | title = School shooting arraignment delayed in school
 | curly = y 
 | url = http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2006/Mar-18-Sat-2006/news/6431035.html
 | agency = [[The Associated Press]]
 | work = [[Las Vegas Review-Journal]]
 | publisher = Sherman Frederick
 | location = [[Las Vegas, Nevada]], [[United States|USA]]
 | date = 2006-03-18
 | accessdate = 2008-11-21
 | quote = Eighth-grader held in gun attack that resulted in two students suffering minor wounds
 }}</ref> He removed the concealed pistol from his coat pocket<ref name="JUDGE_Perry" /> and loaded it with three .38 caliber rounds while in the bathroom.  He chose his target, student Alexander Rueda, 14, at random in a hallway outside the cafeteria.  Before he started firing, a friend of Newman yelled at him to put the gun away, but Newman told him to run.<ref name="LasVegasReview" />  He pulled the trigger twice but the gun did not fire because those [[Chamber (firearms)|chambers]] were empty. He then fired three times at Rueda.  One bullet hit Rueda in the arm and torso, and another ricocheted and hit student Kenzie McKeonin, 14,<ref name="NewsReview">{{cite news
 | first = Kerlin 
 | last =  Kat 
 | coauthors = Dennis Myers
 | title = Shooting shock
 | url = http://www.newsreview.com/reno/Content?oid=48175
 | agency = 
 | work = 
 | publisher = ''NewsReview'' 
 | location = [[Nevada]], [[United States]]
 | date = 2006-03-16
 | accessdate = 2008-12-23
 | quote = 
 }}</ref> in the leg from [[shrapnel]].  The two injured students had no prior relationship or arguments with Newman.<ref name="FoxNews" />  Several students and teachers heard the shots and the athletics teacher, Jencie Fagan, approached Newman and challenged him. Fagan managed to convince Newman to drop his gun and then restrained him until more staff arrived to help.<ref name="FoxNews" /><ref name="KOLOTV" /><ref name="ABCNEWS">{{cite news
 | first = 
 | last = 
 | coauthors = 
 | title = 'Hero' Teacher Stopped Shooting With Hug
 | url = http://abcnews.go.com/GMA/Story?id=1732518&page=1
 | agency = [[Associated Press]] 
 | work = 
 | publisher = [[ABC News]] 
 | location = 
 | date = 2006-03-16
 | accessdate = 2009-01-08
 | quote = 
 }}</ref>

Alexander Rueda was treated at Washoe Medical Center for his wounds and released the same day, while Kenzie McKeonin only needed to be treated at the scene for superficial wounds.<ref name="LATimes" /> The school was placed on [[lockdown]] for an hour and then classes were canceled for the remainder of the day.<ref name="FoxNews" /> The shooting was the second firearm-related incident on Pine Middle School grounds in two weeks, with the previous incident being a man brandishing a gun towards the campus. On this occasion school administrators sent students home as a precaution.<ref name="NewsReview" />

===Motive===
After the shooting, Newman was interviewed by the police and remained determined that he did not want his parents to be present during questioning, however Newman's father had arrived sometime after to ask for the questioning to stop until a lawyer would be consulted.<ref name="Sosandiego" /><ref name="LasVegasReview" /> During questioning Newman stated that he wanted to use the attack as a way to end abuse from his father, brother, and others. He said he was tired of being called "stupid" by them.<ref name="LasVegasReview" /> He researched the [[Columbine High School massacre]] on the [[Internet]] and planned the attack about a week in advance.<ref name="LasVegasReview" /> He conclusively decided against using a knife because "he did not want to be up close when blood came out of any of the victims."<ref name="LasVegasReview" />  The night before the attack, Newman's father had given him a collection of ammunition which included three live .38 caliber rounds. When his parents left the house to eat, he took his mother's handgun from a small safe in his father's closet and hid it in his backpack.<ref name="LasVegasReview" />

== Aftermath ==
Following the shooting, police arrested James Newman and booked him as an adult on charges of suspicion of attempted murder, use of a deadly weapon and use of a firearm by a minor in Washoe County Jail with a [[bail]] of [[United States dollar|$]]150,000.<ref name="LATimes">{{cite news
 | title = Teacher Steps In to End School Shooting
 | curly = y 
 | url = http://articles.latimes.com/2006/mar/15/nation/na-teacher15
 | work = Los Angeles Times
 | publisher = Eddy Hartenstein
 | location = [[Los Angeles]], [[United States]]
 | page = A-21
 | date = 2006-03-15
 | accessdate = 2008-11-21
 }}</ref>  However, his trial was put on hold as prosecutors discussed whether he should be tried as an adult or juvenile.<ref name="LasVegasReview" /> Washoe District Attorney Richard Gammick had announced on March 17 that the evidence given did not support Newman being charged as an adult.<ref name="Sosandiego">{{cite news
 | title = Accused Reno school shooter ordered held
 | curly =  
 | url = http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/nation/20060320-1730-nv-schoolshooting.html
 | agency = [[Associated Press]]
 | work = 
 | publisher = [[Union-Tribune]]
 | location = [[San Diego]], [[California]]
 | page = 
 | date = 2006-03-20
 | accessdate = 2009-01-07
 }}</ref> Eventually, Newman was tried as a juvenile by the Jan Evans Juvenile Justice Center for the charges of two counts of [[Battery (crime)|battery]] with a deadly weapon<ref name="JUDGE_Perry">{{cite news
 | title = 14-year-old suspect's case headed to juvenile court
 | first = Martha
 | last = Bellisle 
 | curly =  
 | url = http://www.judgeperry.com/newman.html
 | work = 
 | publisher = 
 | location = [[Reno, Nevada]] 
 | page = 
 | date = 2006-03-18
 | accessdate = 2008-12-21
 }}</ref> instead of the initial charges and was put under [[house arrest]] until he completed 200 hours of [[community service]].<ref name="WashingtonPost" />

On March 25, 2008, Jencie Fagan was selected as one of three national winners and the Nevada finalist for an Above & Beyond Citizen Honor from the Congressional Medal of Honor Society in the [[Washington D.C.]] ceremony, being recognized for her role in prevention of any further incident in the shooting.<ref name="kolotv2">{{cite news
